{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"14732764-21fd-4abd-9784-fb66c7d87edc","content":"**.NET MAUI's Android build ignores `JAVA_HOME`.** It uses its own JDK resolution via the `$(JavaSdkDirectory)` MSBuild property, which defaults to the **Microsoft OpenJDK** bundled with the Android workload — not your system Temurin install.\n\n### Fix options (pick one):\n\n**Option 1 — Install the expected JDK (recommended):**\n```bash\ndotnet workload install maui\n```\nThis installs/repairs the Microsoft OpenJDK 17 that the build expects.\n\n**Option 2 — Point the build at your Temurin JDK:**\n\nAdd to your `.csproj`:\n```xml\n<PropertyGroup Condition=\"$([MSBuild]::IsOSPlatform('osx'))\">\n  <JavaSdkDirectory>/Library/Java/JavaVirtualMachines/temurin-17.jdk/Contents/Home</JavaSdkDirectory>\n</PropertyGroup>\n```\n\nOr pass it on the command line:\n```bash\ndotnet build -p:JavaSdkDirectory=/Library/Java/JavaVirtualMachines/temurin-17.jdk/Contents/Home\n```\n\nOption 1 is preferred since it keeps you on the JDK version Microsoft tests against.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"e3a295cb-5e76-47ca-8632-f57aac8061eb","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is having a .NET MAUI Android build failure with a Java-related error on macOS. They have Adoptium Temurin JDK 17.0.12 installed with JAVA_HOME pointing to it.\n\nLet me think about common .NET MAUI Android + Java issues:\n\n1. .NET MAUI / Xamarin Android requires a specific JDK version. Starting with .NET 8, MAUI uses JDK 17, but there can be path issues on macOS.\n\n2. On macOS, the typical JAVA_HOME path for Adoptium Temurin would be something like `/Library/Java/JavaVirtualMachines/temurin-17.jdk/Contents/Home`.\n\n\n3. The build system has its own bundled Microsoft OpenJDK and uses the `$(JavaSdkDirectory)` MSBuild property to determine which JDK to use—it doesn't automatically respect the JAVA_HOME environment variable. Even though they have JDK 17.0.12 installed, the build might not be finding or using it correctly on macOS.\n\n4. If they want to force the build to use their Temurin installation instead of the bundled Microsoft JDK, they'd need to explicitly set `<JavaSdkDirectory>` in the project file or pass it as an MSBuild property during the build.\n\n5. The most likely culprits given what they've told me: either the macOS JAVA_HOME path isn't pointing to the correct subdirectory within the Temurin installation, or the .NET Android build system is defaulting to its own JDK and encountering an issue there. Without the exact error message, I'd need to ask them to verify the JAVA_HOME path is set to the full Home directory path and check what the actual build error says. The main solutions are setting up the Microsoft OpenJDK that comes with the Android workload, explicitly configuring the `JavaSdkDirectory` property in the project file to point to Temurin, or on macOS ensuring the `JAVA_HOME` environment variable correctly references the Temurin installation path. But without seeing the exact error message, I'm wondering if there's a specific compatibility issue between .NET 8 and Temurin 17.0.12 that I should consider. path/to/jdk` on the command line. The real issue is that .NET MAUI's Android build doesn't rely on `JAVA_HOME` — it uses its own JDK resolution mechanism. The cleanest fix is either installing Microsoft's bundled OpenJDK through the workload or explicitly setting the `JavaSdkDirectory` property to point to the Temurin installation.","outputTokens":1786,"requestId":"044D:75CA6:B49322:CD2B31:6A0279A8"},"id":"9b7ca2d9-d977-4465-901f-18c7104b52cc","timestamp":"2026-05-12T00:52:32.186Z","parentId":"f569ffb2-3d23-437a-bfba-c93bc39eda41"}
